^*Bhondo717:^*N Lots to discuss.  First the defense. Your diamond duck was fine aggie.  If you don't duck, you set up two diamond tricks for moe, so at worst you traded tricks.  Remember, 2nd hand low is rarely wrong, even when it seems so. You have to get in the habit of thinking, "I must have a very good reason NOT to play 2nd hand low."  And you had none in this hand. The best reason, for example, is if it is the setting trick. Another reason is if you think you need to be on lead to prevent partner from having an awkward lead. And, only very occasionally, you play high if you are sure declarer is out after this round.|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


NT|^B@2 
Now, when aggie gets in with a spade, she should play the Ace of diamonds, causing moe to run out of trumps.  Never be afraid to make declarer ruff. at worst, it is a safe play, and often it makes him run out of trumps prematurely.  Had you done that aggie, we would have beat the hand. So not only did ducking the ace of diamonds not cost us a trick, but it gave us a way to beat the hand, had you followed through. Hard for you to see, but just remember that making declarer ruff is rarely a bad play. |
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


NT|^B@2
It is at worst a neutral defense because declarer can ruff if he wants anyway. A kib just brought up a good point. It is not right to give declarer a ruff and sluf. So, if both dummy and declarer are out of a suit, you should not play it.  Because, then you are giving declarer a free discard he would not have otherwise.  It is ok to give declarer a ruff, as long as one of the hands still has the suit, or one of the hands is out of trump.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


