^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his @E@3important instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls" which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you will find many more.|fp|2|at|  

                                   
2nd hand low is rarely wrong, even when it seems so. You have to get in the habit of thinking, "I must have a very good reason NOT to play 2nd hand low."

Never be afraid to make declarer ruff. at worst, it is a safe play, and often it makes him run out of trumps prematurely.

It is not right to give declarer a ruff and sluf. So, if both dummy and declarer are out of a suit, you should not play it.

One level bids are forcing over a takeout double.

Shortness in the opponents suit is very powerful, and should make you upgrade your hand.

